This photo is now available as a limited edition print through my online print store. With code “LAUNCH30”, prints like this one start as low as $84 USD until December 31st. Last year I photographed a group of passionate environmentalists fiercely opposed to the Trans Mountain Pipeline Expansion Project. When they felt as though their lawful methods of protest ran dry, they began building treehouses along the construction route of the pipeline with the goal of stopping it. This peaceful direct action was spearheaded by Simon Fraser University professor Tim Takaro. 

The story was documented alongside writer Emily Kelsall (pictured in images 2,3,4 & 5). It’s published as a three part story in the @natobserver and some of the images will be featured in @chatelainemag soon. 

To find out how we snuck past security, the fate of the professor who started it all and how everything came to an end check out the links to stories I’ve included in my bio! 

#environmentalism #stoptmx #transmountain #conservarionphotography #photojournalism #vancouverphotographer

Perception
40x60’’
Acrylic on canvas

Working from the reference imagery of Ian Harland, ‘Perception’ was an interesting piece to create because of the direct eye contact. In my work, I aim to replace fear and misunderstanding with empathy and connection in animal and human relations. Often direct eye contact elicits discomfort or fear, so the challenge was capturing a sense of serenity. I think it really came down to a symbiotic sharing of space, with respect for nature on Ian’s side crucial to the interaction.

“On the banks of a river that was well-known to me, I set out to photograph black bears fishing for salmon from a distance. The location where I had positioned myself next to the river was rarely populated by bears due to the salmon run being stronger in other areas. However, the competition for the best fishing spots caused smaller individuals to seek new locations such as this interaction of a calm passing while making direct eye contact.” - Ian Harland

Sunrise in the Yukon. Dall's sheep are a species of wild sheep native to the mountains of Alaska and western Canada. They are known for their large, curved horns and white fur which helps them blend in with their snowy habitat. They are typically found in high-altitude alpine and subalpine habitats. I’m hoping to spend more times with these guys soon! #dallssheep #wildlifephotography #canada #yukon

While many black bears enter a state of dormancy known as hibernation to survive harsh winters, not all bears hibernate, and the duration of hibernation can vary greatly depending on factors such as location, food availability, and reproductive status. For instance, black bears in warmer climates such as Florida may not hibernate at all, while those in colder regions such as Alaska may hibernate for up to six months. Regardless of their hibernation habits, black bears are incredible survivors, adapting to the challenges of life in the wild with tenacity and resilience. #bears #blackbear #wildlifephotography #vancouverisland #britishcolumbia #vancouver #canada

I spent a few days up in Churchil (Northern Canada) last July without any expectations of seeing the aurora because of the seemingly endless sunlight. When the sky doesn’t get fully dark in the summer, a very strong light show is needed to make the aurora visible. And that’s exactly what we got. In the early morning hours, I was woken up by my guide telling us to get out of bed because the lights were outside. To be honest, I was expecting a faint glow at best. Once I got outside and saw the bright green pillars dancing in the sky, I soon realized that it was the best light show of my life. Chasing northern lights can be addicting, and it’s one of the reasons I’m now back in Northern Canada, the Yukon this time, in search of these beautiful displays of light. I’m getting close to the end of my two week trip and I’ve seen them most nights (some nights quite faint). I can’t wait to share more moments like these soon with you all! #northernlights #aurora #churchil #canada #manitoba

Did you catch the northern lights show last night? Sadly, Vancouver was blanketed in clouds, so I couldn’t even attempt to photograph them. Luckily, I just returned from a two-week trip to the Yukon where I witnessed the neon pillars dancing across the sky most nights. None were quite as mesmerizing as the ones I captured in this video. The catch? It was the coldest night of my life, with temperatures dipping to -35°C and wind chill making it feel like -50°C! As you can see, even my eyelashes froze! #northernlights #aurora #yukon #canada
Until next winter. Which is your favorite? I think mine is the polar bear shot at the end. #wildlifephotography #winter #wildlifephotographer

Swimming alongside pelagic sharks like the Shortfin Mako is a magical experience. These fascinating creatures, who have likely never encountered a person before, exhibit a sense of curiosity as they try to discern what you are to them - competition for food, a potential predator, prey, or something inconsequential.

This individual would descend into the depths where fading light and particles floating in the ocean would render it invisible only to swim up again and begin circling. 

I wasn’t sure if I was going to post this photo because I didn’t want to perpetuate the misconception that sharks are vicious and out to harm people. As someone who has had the opportunity to swim with about 10 sharks during this recent trip, I can confidently say that I never felt worried for my safety. The number of shark fatalities per year is relatively low, with only about 5 reported cases, most of which occur during ocean board sports like surfing.

On the other hand, humans are responsible for an estimated 100 million shark deaths per year due to various activities such as fishing and finning. It's crucial to acknowledge the importance of shark conservation and promote responsible interactions with these magnificent creatures to ensure their survival in our oceans.

#shark #makoshark #mexico #underwaterphotography @bajasharkexperience

In the process of updating my website recently, I stumbled upon some photographs that I had been commissioned to take for a tourism agency back when I was 19. I thought it would be nice to share them once more.

My first week was a lively adventure, exploring the colorful streets of Havana with my client. We learned how to craft the perfect Mojito from Fidel Castro's personal waiter, stayed in fancy hotels, and immersed ourselves in the city's vibrant culture. After my client's itinerary was completed, I decided to extend my stay in Cuba, planning out a few extra days of exploration that were quite different from what I had previously experienced.

I purchased a bus ticket to a town renowned for its role in producing tobacco for the famous Cuban cigars. However, what truly fascinated me about this town were the imposing limestone cliffs, and the handful of individuals who climbed them despite not being allowed or having a mountain culture like we have here. I was able to find one of them on airbnb and got to climb myself.

Looking back, this trip remains one of my favorites. By gathering images for this post and writing about it, it definitely makes me want to revisit soon!

As a bonus, I've included a brief video of me playing the only song I could remember on the piano at that time. It seems like I was quite fixated on playing it as quickly as possible. 

#cuba #cubaphotography #travelphotography

Over the last couple of years I’ve had the pleasure of photographing the staff training for @kayakwithwhales on Quadra Island. It’s been a fun mix of kayak surfing, cold dipping in bioluminescent waters, eating delicious food, and unwinding in the sauna. All while sharing stories and learning from around 20 sea kayak guides. #quadraisland #britishcolumbia #seakayaking #kayaking #kayaksurfing

Recently, I embarked on a three day adventure, my sights set on the elusive Coastal Wolf, one of the most sought after animals on the west Coast of Canada. Together with Andrew and Mike from @coastalrainforestsafaris , Andrew Eames writing for Financial Times and fellow photographer @taylormichaelburk , we journeyed into the heart of the beautiful T̕łat̕ła̱sikwa̱la territory located on the rugged edge of Northern Vancouver Island.

Our base was a secluded island, which was recently discovered to have wolves living on it. Under old growth cedars we set up shelter and woke up to the sound of howling of wolves from our tent. Every day, as the tide dropped and revealed a buffet of intertidal life for the canine inhabitants of the island, we set out on the zodiac boat in search of them. 

Searching for wildlife like wolves must come with the understanding that we may leave without seeing what we were hoping to, but during this trip we were lucky enough to have great sighting every day. #coastalwolf #wolf #northernvancouverisland #britishcolumbia #wildlifephotography

Highlining adventures over the last few days…

Here’s some backstory of for the first shot. A few days ago, @matthplante , an enthusiastic highliner, shared a vision with me for a highline site he had recently established- a scene with someone suspended from silks from a highline , another person walking a shorter highline, and a kayak taking a plunge down a waterfall . Despite the time it would take to get here , his passion convinced me to embark on a near 2-hour drive to this remote spot.

To get the perfect angle, I had to rappel down a cliffside laden with dense and prickly shrubbery. The ascent was equally adventurous, requiring the use of an ascender system. Matthieu and I were unsure if the shot would be possible, as we had no kayakers lined up, but the waterfall was a hotspot for them so we had hope.

After waiting for a bit, @selina_blewitt and @mozart821 spotted kayakers upstream and it was action time. With no time to lose, I quickly deployed my drone, and maneuvered it into position, narrowly avoiding trees.

After successfully capturing the shot and safely landing the drone, Matt and I celebrated. No more kayakers passed through that day, but with spirits high, I took to the top highline for a session of my own. 

The last couple slides of this carousel are of me. l walked on a 130m line for my first time! 

#highliner #kayak #whitewaterkayaking #britishcolumbia #vancouver #canada #highline

Here's a personal favorite photo of mine, featuring @dylan_mc_smith_ tackling one of the most beautiful climbs around. Even though digital tools now make it easy to merge multiple shots, there was something special about nailing this photo in a single frame. 

This wasn't a fluke - we planned meticulously to ensure the Milky Way would be right behind Dylan. It took us until 2am, but the result was absolutely worth it! 

I should also mention that this climb is very difficult and Dylan held the crux multiple times, in this photo for the full 8 second exposure. 

#vancouver #squamish #britishcolumbia #explorebc #squamishclimbing #vancouverclimbing #deepwatersolo

Portraits of a Red Fox in the Yukon. In the winter, these beautiful animals develop thick warm fur to help combat the freezing temperatures. 

Throughout my time in the Yukon, I came across several foxes, all with very different temperaments. Some would run off as soon as we’d stop the vehicle, while others like this habituated urban fox went from home to home looking for food like a child on Halloween. #redfox #yukon #whitehorse #fox
Looking forward to heading back to Phantom Lake in a couple of days with my friends over at @seatoskyair #squamish #vancouver #britishcolumbia #explorebc #canada #floatplane

Freediving with Blue Sharks off the coast of Mexico. Not only was this the first time I had ever photographed sharks, it was my first time ever seeing them in the wild. It was fascinating watching them trying to figure me out. Their elegance stood in stark contrast to their pelagic neighbors the Mako Shark. #blueshark #mexico #shark #sharkdiving #freediving #underwaterphotography

A couple nights ago I embarked on an overnight backcountry hike with @liron_gertsman_photography , with the hopes of encountering wildlife and taking in the beautiful views of the mountains near Vancouver.  On the drive to the trailhead Liron mentioned that there was a chance of Aurora but that it likely wouldn’t be strong and that the data indicated that peak activity was during the day, making it invisible to us. 

After a day filled with 4 black bears, 5 White Tailed Prarmigan and beautiful views all around, Liron saw a faint glow overhead as we were preparing for bed. The Aurora grew stronger and stronger until dancing bands of light were visible overhead, a rare event in a location as southerly as Vancouver. 

#northernlights #aurora #vancouver #britishcolumbia #canada

social_posts.post_text:
I recently spent an unforgettable 2 weeks kayaking in Gwaii Haanas, Haida Gwaii on assignment for @kayakwithwhales . 

Photos 9 and 10 are of Kevin Hennig, owner of Raincoast Breads, the first fine-dining establishment in Canada with a permit to forage wild food. I joined him one day as he scoured for wild plants and mushrooms. 

This journey would not have been nearly as enjoyable, insightful, or inspiring, if it weren’t for the wonderful guides. Big thanks to @kellerudie for putting up with me both weeks and doubling as my personal encyclopedia. @alx.emily for teaching me bird calls with her live action interpretations from field guide descriptions. And Renee for her impressive storytelling skills and positive energy.

I’d also like to thank the Haida Watchmen who graciously shared their powerful history and stories with us. 

Haida Gwaii, is a truly remarkable destination and I highly recommend everyone visit if given the opportunity. 

#haidagwaii #gwaiihaanas #canada #britishcolumbia #explorebc

Taking a walk on the wild side at the F.I.S.H Festival in France, organized by the incredible @houledouce! From being petrified of heights during the first couple of days to setting a new personal record one of the longest highlines at the festival, this journey has been nothing short of exhilarating. Grateful for the wonderful community, stunning shows, and the chance to brush up on my French. The adventure didn’t stop there - post-festival, I joined fellow highliners for a rock climbing escapade in the nearby mountains. Hopefully I can go to more of these festivals in the future! #highline #france

A joint photographic adventure with Liron Gertsman Photography in the breathtaking Yukon territory of Canada. We began during the day with a quest for the perfect compositions, knowing we had a decent chance of getting the Aurora. We discovered this vast scene, not for its immediate landscape, but for the potential drama it could unfold – a vast canvas of untouched snow and distant mountains, waiting to be animated by the Northern Light spectacle. As night fell, the aurora borealis did not disappoint. Its green and red pillars converged above with the Milky Way draping its way between them, crafting stunning leading lines that drew the eye to the heart of the photo.

#northernlights #aurora #yukon #canada

In parks around the world, you'll find those iconic 'postcard' spots – beautiful, but often crowded. Venturing into the backcountry, however, offers a different experience. Here, you can immerse yourself in equally stunning vistas in solitude. Away from the boardwalks, fences, and flurry of selfie sticks, you connect with nature in its purest form.
